  "doi": "10.1016/j.immuni.2009.11.003",
  "title": "T cell receptor cross-reactivity directed by antigen-dependent tuning of peptide-MHC molecular flexibility.",
  "journal": "Immunity",
  "year": 2009,
  "authors": "Borbulevych OY, Piepenbrink KH, Gloor BE, Scott DR, Sommese RF, Cole DK, Sewell AK, Baker BM."
 },
 "executive_summary": "The A6 TCR recognizes two structurally similar peptides\u2014Tax (LLFGYPVYV) and Tel1p (MLWGYLQYV)\u2014both presented by HLA-A2, despite forming substantially different interfaces with the receptor. Conformational differences arise not only in the peptides and TCR but also unexpectedly in the MHC molecule itself, with peptide-dependent modulation of HLA-A2 dynamics distinguishing the two complexes; these differences are undetectable in free pMHC structures and cannot be explained by classical induced-fit binding. This work reveals that differential \"tuning\" of MHC molecular flexibility by different peptide ligands\u2014rather than static structural mimicry alone\u2014underlies TCR cross-reactivity, fundamentally altering our understanding of how the immune system accommodates structural diversity and recognizes related antigens. The findings have implications for TCR engineering and predicting cross-reactive responses in both viral infection (Tax from HTLV-1) and other contexts where TCR recognition of multiple peptides is biologically important.",
